0df 4 M 414 Star lae FO I N 19.91\n10 Iteck 197 7.91 ToIEIFO ION till\ntteel 1.17 7.12 Tee Fill 7.41 111\nTelacce I N 912 Halt See F 0 9.111014\n\u2022HUlties 1.191014 Wat Cant FO 111 HI\nIr IN tin 11.1111.11 us lac F 0 IIT 147\nCarla Mtt 19 01 11.47 Ua Scl FO I N I N\nNsaFONCT 1.12 4.21 Ua FI Cm 111114 M\nNea FO NOS 1.17 Val llaa F 0 1.41 I.M\n*Neroack 27 59 22.99 Til l lac F 0 441 414\nHe Fool 2.11 7.41 Tel l S9I 1.27 741\nlie FI ltd 1.41 7.11 well St lae 0.14 771\ntacp lac 7 M I.M Mask M lae 7.M I.M\nlacs lies 177 7.11 Welllta F 0 11.17 92. N\nHstlt Ik F 0 0.17 11 M Wkitekll FI 11.14 12 M\nIksn Fat F 0 I.N 1.71 Nisceasla 4 N 1.17\niHtltlrro 192 171; \u2018Net asset eolae.\nHall Im FI 5)71 1.211\nincreased FNMA receipts on\nthe issues $1,142,500 over what\nthey would have been if the\noffering had been at par. Just\na month ago, FNMA offered 4-\nyear debentures at par and the\ncoupon was 3Vi per cent.\nB&O Earnings Down\nSharply From 1957\nNet income of Baltimore and\nOhio Railroad was $631,804 in\nJanuary, compared with sl.-\n527,625 in January last year,\nthe road reported.\nThe month\u2019s revenues\namounted to $32,966,869 vs.\n$38,337,883 a year ago. Operat\ning expenses totaled $27,392,-\n604 vs. $31,664,169.\nEaker Sees Sharp Gain\nIn Douglas Missiles\nMissiles orders of Douglas\nAircraft Co. now exceed 31 per\ncent of the company\u2019s military\nbusiness and may reach 50 per\ncent in 1959, reported Lt. Gen.\nIra C. Eaker, USAF, retired,\nvice president of the company,\nhere yesterday.\nAddressing the Washington\nSociety of Investment Analysts\nat the Occidental Restaurant,\nGen. Eaker said missiles ac\ncounted for 16 per cent of\nDouglas\u2019 military business In\nthe fiscal year ended November\n30, 1956, rose to 31 per cent\nin 1957 and will exceed this\nmark in the current fiscal\nperiod.\nThe company's new DC-8 jet\nairliners have a great future\nalthough many airports will\nhave to be enlarged to accomo\ndate them and commercial air\nlines are in a difficult situation\nas a result of rising costs, he\nsaid.\nGarflnckel Board Vote*\nQuarterly Dividends\nDirectors of Julius Garflnckel\nSt Co., Inc., yesterday declared\nregular quarterly dividends of\n40 cents a share on common\nstock and 28 Vi cents a share\non the 4.5 per cent convertible\npreferred stock.\nBoth dividends will be paid\nMarch 31 to stockholders pf\nrecord March 14.\nCoal Export Association\nOpens Office in D. C.\nThe High Volatile Coals Ex\nport Association, Inc., has been\norganized by coal producers of\nthe southern Appalachian area\nand headquarters have been\nopened here with Charles R.\nCurtin of Cincinnati in charge\nas executive vice president.\nMember firms have produc\ntion of well over 65 million tons\nof high volatile coal annually.\nHeadquarters are in the South\nern Building.\n|G. J. Mitchell, Jr., Co.\nForms Insurance Firm\nG. J. Mitchell, Jr., Co., yes\nterday announced the founding\nof an affiliated Insurance com\npany. Estate Planning Associ\nates, Inc.\nThe affiliate will operate Ini\ntially in Maryland, Virginia and\nthe District of Columbia and\nwill devote special attention to\nestate planning.\nRetail Bakers Week\nTo Be Celebrated\nDistrict Commissioners have\ndesigned the period from\nMarch 2 through March 8 as\nNational Retail Bakers Week at\nthe request of the Associated\nRetail Bakers of the Greater\nWashington Area.\nAugust W. Neuland of Neu\nland's bakery, president of the\nassociation and other baking\nleaders attended the Commis\nsioners\u2019 signing of the pro\nclamation yesterday.\nMerger Hinted\nCINCINNATI. Feb. 27 UP).\nArthur B. Sinkler of Lancas\nter, Pa., president of the Ham\nilton Watch Co., told the Cin\ncinnati Times-Star yesterday\nthat \u201csomething is brewing\u201d\nwith the Gruen Watch Co., of\nthis city.\nCHTGO LIVESTOCK\nCHICAGO, Feb. *7 i\u00ab lUSDA).\nSalable hogs 6.Sou; active and uneven.\nJS to 40 higher on butcher*. Instance*\n50 higher late; early clearance: sows\nscarce; mostly Oft higher: good local\npacker demand, but only a lew cars\nsold for shipment; 2*B 200-270 lb\nbutchers 20.00-20.35; several lota 1-2\n200-225 Tb 20 40-20 05; around 200\nhead mosUy la these weights sorted\nfor weight and grade go.fu: IS head\nlot selecteed Is 2204 b at 19,00: weights\nover 270 lb scarce; a few lots mostly\nOs 270-310 lbs 19.65-20.00: a deck No.\n3s 326 lbs 19.50; weights under 800\nlbs scarce larger lots mlged grade 400-\n550 lb sows 17.75-18.75; a few lots\n325-400 lbs 18.75-19.25; a small lot\nIs 280 lbs at 19.50.\nSalable cattle 2,000; calves 100: high\nchoice and prime cattle absent, steers\naverage choice and below acarce; about\nsteady, heifers low good gnd below\nsteady; overage good to overage choice\nweek; spots 50 lower: connera and\nutility cows steady to 25 lower; com\nmercial and standard cows about\nSteady: bulls about steady with\nWednesday's close, vealers steady to\n1.00 lower, the first downturn In vealer\nprices in many weeks; stockers and\nfeederi steady; a load of average\nchoice 1,075 ib slaughter steers 28.50.\ngood and choice 1,150 lb down 24.00-\n2, .>0; standard to low good 21.00-\nj-3'SO: 3 loads good to mostly choice\n950 lb heifers 25.00; standard and\ngood 20.00-24.00; utility gnd commer\ncial cowg 16 50-18 50; a few standard\ncows up to 20.00; canners and cutters\n1350-16.60: a few light shelly can\nners dewn to 11.50; utility and com\nmercial bulls 19 50-22.00; sood and\nchoice vealers 30.00-36.00; a few light\nculls as low as 12.00; aood and choice\n835-1,050 lb feeding steers 25 50-\n26.00.\nFOREIGN EXCH'GE\nI _ NEW YORK. Feb 27 <46.\u2014:Foreign\nExchange rates, Oreat Britain In dol\nlars, ethers In cents (unchanged un\nless otherwise noted):\nCanadian dollar In New York open\nmarket 2 6/32 per cent premium or\n102 15** United States cent* up 1/32.\nEurope: Oreat Britain (Pound)\n97 81 5/32. up 11/32; 30-day futures\n2 80A, up 11/32; 8i)-d*y futures\n2. 79(4, up H; 90-day futures 2.7811,\nup 13/32; Belclum (franc) 2.04),V\nFrance (franc) .23%: Germany (West\nern 1 (deutache mark) 23.50; Holland\n1 (guilder! 26 38',. up 00%: Italy (lira)\nl.fsVi; Portugal (atcudo) 3 50; Sweden\n(krona) _ 19714; swltserland (franei\n1 (free) 23.34; Denmark 1 krone) 14.50.\nm M\n\nCAPITAL VlSlTO\u00df\u2014Her\nbert L. Barnet, president\nof the Pepsi-Cola Co., was\nhere today for the open\ning of a two-day confer\nence of his company\u2019s\nregional bottling execu\ntives at the Mayflower\nHotel. He spoke on the\ngeneral business outlook\nand company promotional\nplans. Bottlers of the\nMiddle Atlantic States at\ntended.\nMERRILL LYNCH\nALTERS NAME\nON SATURDAY\nNEW YORK, Feb. 27 UP).\n\u2014The Beane of Merril\nLynch, Pierce, Fenner St\nBeane will soon become the\nBeane of J. R. Wllliston\nBeane.\nAlphus C. Beane, whose\nresignation from the Mer\nrill Lynch, etc., firm is\neffective Saturday, will join\nJ. R. Williston St Co. on\nApril 1. The Williston firm\nwill become J. R. Williston'\nBeane, it was disclosed\ntoday.\nMerrill Lynch will be\ncome Merrill Lynch, Pierce,\nFenner St Smith on Satur\nday. The Smith is Win\nthrop Smith, directing\npartner, as previously an\nnounced.\nPEOPLE\nIN\nBUSINESS\nHarry Merkin, who celebrat\ned his 30th anniversary with\nEquitable Life Assurance So\nciety, led the entire southern\ndepartment of the society in\nJanuary. He was fourth in the\nNation for ordinary produc\ntion. He heads the Harry\nMerkin Co. agency of Equit\nable.\nJames E. Barrett of Wash\nington weis elected one of three\nassistants to the president of\nMutual of Omaha to co-ordi\nnate plans for the company\u2019s\n50th anniversary. As assistant\nvice president, he has super\nvised the firm\u2019s airline travel\ninsurance in 37 countries.\nSamuel Levy of David Rich\nard was re-elected a director\nof the National Association of\nRetail Clothiers and Fur\nnishers.\nMarty B. Diamond of Silver\nSpring has been named assis\ntant manager of the Washing\nton stgency of Mutual Life In\nsurance Co. ol New York.\n/Dr. John Menkart has joined\nthe staff of Harris Research\nLaboratories. He formerly was\nwith the Textile Research In\nstitute at Princeton.\nGerald M. Exten has become\nchief engineers of Polytronic\nResearch, nc\u201e at Rockville. He\nformerly was vice president of\nLinguatronics, Inc.\nDon Michelson has been\nnamed sales supervisor for\nWorthington Corp. in this area.\nJoseph L. Pavlock has been\nnamed vice president and east\nern trade sales manager for\nHarrison Paint St Varnish Co.\nof Canton, Ohio, with head\nquarters in Silver Spring.\nJohn J. Tobin, jr\u201e has been\nnamed manager of reservations\nfor American Airlines at Na\ntional Airport.\nDividend Reduced\nNEW YORK, Feb. 27 UP\nInspiration Consolidated Cop\n'per Co. today reduced its divi\ndend to 50 cents a share, pay\nable March 21 to stockholders\nof record March 7. The com\npany paid 75 cents a share in\neach of the three previous\n\u2022quarters.\nFRENCH SPANISH\nITALIAN GERMAN\n\u2022T 3 ENGLISH IEARN ANY\nMULISH LANGUAGE\nIK.* QUICKLY\nBERLITZ\nBRAND NEW! NEVER DRIVEN\n1958\nCHRYSLER\nWINDSOR\n4\u2018DOOR SEDANS\nTORSION-AIRE RIDE\nTORQUEFLITE\nTRANSMISSION,\nTURN SIGNALS\nSAFETY DASH, HEATER\nm\nFULL PRICE, DELIVERED\nUNLIMITED QUANTITT!\nWQjy\nvDSQbeBbI\n3901 RHODE\nISLAND AVE. N.E.\nWA. 7-7000\nPeoples Drug to Offer\n30-DayCharge Accounts\nIn a marked departure from\nprevious policy. Peoples Drug\nStores has become a member\nof Central Charge Service and\nwill offer a charge account\nservice for its customers, effec\ntive today.\nIn a letter to customers, Peo\nples\u2019 treasurer, H. J. Althouse\nsaid many customers already\nmembers of Central Charge\nService will welcome the oppor\ntunity to use an account with\nhis firm.\n\"If you have not enjoyed the\nconvenience of a 30-day Central\nCharge account, we have made\narrangements to open one for\nyou, and within a few days\nyou will receive a charge-card\ntoken and a booklet listing the\nseveral hundred other selected\nLiquidation\nIs Asked for\nLoew's, Inc.\nNEW YORK, Feb. 27 (/P).\nA suggestion that Loew\u2019s, Inc.,\nthe Nation\u2019s largest movie\nmaker, liquidate its film studios\nas \u201ceconomically unsound\" was\nmade at the annual meeting\ntoday.\nThe proposal was made by a\nformer Municipal Court justice, i\nLouis J. Goldstein, appearing\nUtrl J l ll j\nTILI iiPiiWlMl i ji 33\nLh I\u2014l Hundreds Os Values Marked Down Te Rock Bottom!\nnnfjsH IvJ tMa Prizes in Western Auto's Big Win-A-NewXar Contest\nI 'misSSXB Silent Sentry\nTube Type. Regular I H\u00bbfSjW AKD\nOutright 28.85, now Nothing T\u00ab Buy! f (Ms \u00ab*/!.fV* M,y\n*1.50 Down I J Plui Tax No Obligation! I H Whufa,\nV j| 20 YVockly w J i Tii* Jest Follow Easy\nHBHShF I IFiTIMI GUARANTEE I. U\u00ab\u00ab kntry coupon h\u00abr.of g\u00abt by a 4rawia\u00ab aa* *#fi\nf fcNl fc WWftllllll I\u25a0\u25a0 on* frac at your Western Auta ti opprosimotely sia\nL or Western Auta Associate store. after contest dotes. A winners'\nDavis and Wizard res are guaranteed against: All road list will b* s*pt upon request\nhazards including blowouts, cuts, bruises; and all defects Co ,0 r accompanied by stamped, self-\nV in workmanship and materials for ttaod lift of th* f \u00b0J 1 tJ' 5 w addressed envelope to Western\nS tire without limit as to time or mileage Tb* guoronte* yeors old of oMer Py uno Auto, 2107 Grand. Koosos City.\nnever capirca while thcre\u2019t tread on your tires! '\u201cV. Missouri.\nWestern Auto, We.tern Auto 4 Co\u00dffnt t ~k jict Fodcrol.\nDealers, its odv.rt,s,n\u00bb oyanccs, St# y t \u201e4 Local Re\u00abulot.ons.\ntfct\u00dfW. Ttui, t# My, not mcliidcd i*\n*l ijfll J .t8U.......\nHr JUIMiMNHM f Western Auto^Satisfactlon\u201d\nFor Your Old Battery on a j ,S) c ,#u Thi A-1 j\nmZARR j j\nBattery mm Q P I Homo (Fleosc Print)\nReg. 12.45 j* 4\nOutright j\n/V m t 48-Mo. Wizard Sentry. 6-V. With old battery, 13.95 o, Mrt Coupon at Store Contest Clotoa Mae. Z 9, I*SB J\n9 V 36-Mo. Wizard Da Luza. 6-V. With old battery, 9.